03974nam a22005535i 9780774834117DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20172017xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748341177 a10.59962/97807748341172doi  a(DE-B1597)661491  a(OCoLC)965746940  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aDK771 A3bZ36 2017 7aHIS0080002bisacsh04a957/.708223  aNK 7700qDE-24/20sred2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/126244:1 aZatsepine, Victor, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBeyond the Amur :bFrontier Encounters between China and Russia, 1850–1930 /cVictor Zatsepine. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2017] 4c©2017  a1 online resource (240 p.) :b20 figs, 9 tables  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aContemporary Chinese Studies00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tFigures and Tables -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Spelling -- tIntroduction -- tA River Runs through It -- tThey Came from Everywhere -- tFur, Gold, and Local Trade -- tImperial Russian Expansionism -- tChinese Migrants in Frontier Towns -- tA Railway Runs through It -- tConflict and War -- tFading Frontiers -- tConclusion -- tAppendix A -- tAppendix B -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tContemporary Chinese Studies0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBeyond the Amur describes the distinctive frontier society that developed in the Amur, a river region that shifted between Qing China and Imperial Russia as the two empires competed for natural resources. Although official imperial histories depict the Amur as a distant battleground between rival empires, this colourful history of a region and its people tells a different story. Drawing on both Russian and Chinese sources, Victor Zatsepine shows that both empires struggled to maintain the border. But much to the chagrin of imperial administrators, various peoples – Chinese, Russian, Indigenous, Japanese, Korean, Manchu, and Mongol – moved freely across it in pursuit of work and trade, exchanging ideas and knowledge as they adapted to the harsh physical environment. By viewing the Amur as a unified natural economy caught between two empires, Zatsepine highlights the often-overlooked influence of regional developments on imperial policies and the importance of climate and geography to local, state, and imperial histories.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311127365508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017z978311127619908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311141793640uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077483411740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774834117423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774834117/original  a978-3-11-127365-5  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-127619-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2017b2017  a978-3-11-141793-6  University of British Columbia Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles